<dl id="n18060h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n18" href="#n18060h">N18 (VI.B.8)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n18all.htm#n18060h"> 60(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the hat trick <font face="wake">P</font> <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n18060h"><li>FW 486.07 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#n18060h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#n18060h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n18060h">MS BL 47484a-42</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:177 <a name="rAd4" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rAd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd4.htm#n18060h">Draft: III&sect;3A.4</a> IT 250703-8/4: <mark>THE HAT TRICK</mark> Mr. Chamberlain considered that the point at issue had been sufficiently discussed and moved the closure. Miss Wilkinson, the lady representative for Middlesbrough, desired to raise a point of order, but since the motion for the closure had been put from the Chair, it was essential that she should address the Chairman, remaining seated and wearing a hat. Miss Wilkinson for the moment was in a quandary, as her wealth of auburn hair was uncovered. Suddenly, however, on the bench behind her she descried a straw hat belonging to Colonel Harry Day, and promptly annexed it. The House rocked with laughter as she poised it on her head, where it remained so delicately balanced that it was in imminent danger of falling off with the slightest movement.</li> </ul> </dd></dl>
